default5
default              
defaultThe Law Society is concerned that the test remains fundamentally discriminatory and potentially unlawful under English and EU law.
default2.5.1
default              
defaultThe recent MOJ consultation 
defaultJudicial review – proposals for further reform
default omitted to refer to the proposal in the earlier 
defaultTransforming Legal Aid
default consultation paper to impose a 12 months lawful residency requirement for eligibility for civil legal aid. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTh
defaultat proposal is clearly intended to restrict access to the courts. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt will have a particular impact on people challenging the decisions of public bodies in relation to asylum and immigration status.
default&#xa0;
default The Government has had to acknowledge the overwhelming c
defaultriticism of the proposal by exempting certain classes of people from the residence test.
default&#xa0;
default Nonetheless the Law Society remains of the view that the introduction of a residency test is not compatible with the European Convention on Human Rights or Common Law
default rights of access to the courts.
default&#xa0;
default It cannot be squared with Article 14 (prohibition of discrimination) when combined with Article 6 (right to a fair trial).
default&#xa0;
default The residency test would discriminate between people in relation to proceedings before the courts 
defaultand for the purposes of legal aid eligibility.
default&#xa0;
default2.6
default              
defaultThe success rate in appeals to the Tribunal against immigration decisions in managed migration ca
defaultses (e.g. those seeking to work or study in the UK lawfully) stands at around 50%. This suggests that 
defaultpreliminary 
defaultdecision-making is poor. Removing the right of appeal in all these cases will mean that the only way to challenge such decisions through an in
defaultdependent judicial process is by way of judicial review. 
default2.6.1
default              
defaultMany such migrants (or potential migrants) would previously have been eligible for legal aid to challenge a negative decision by way of judicial review. Unfortunately the soon-to-be-introduced
default Residence Test will mean that such people are excluded from legal aid. By definition these people will not meet the Residence Test because either they will not be lawfully resident by the time they are able to seek to challenge a negative decision (contin
defaultuing leave under section 3C of the Immigration Act 1971 will cease once a decision is made on administrative review (clause 11 Immigration Bill 2013)) or they will be outside the UK. Those inside the UK will automatically become 
defaultoverstayers
default at this point a
defaultnd could face criminal sanction despite being the victim of a potentially unlawful decision. The number of people placed in this position will be significant in light of the success rate cited above. 
default2.6.2
default              
defaultMoreover the proposed changes in the Immigration
default Bill
default&#xa0;
defaultwill further limit rights of appeal in immigration cases. This means that many decisions made in managed migration cases will not be able to be judicially challenged as there will be no right of appeal and no legal aid for judicial review. This will 
defaultseverely restrict access to justice for those wishing to lawfully enter or remain in the United Kingdom
default.
default 
